"Stich H.B., Brinker A.","Oligotrophication outweighs effects of global warming in a large, deep, stratified lake ecosystem",2010,"Global Change Biology","16","2",,"877","888",,,10.1111/j.1365-2486.2009.02005.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78149256572&partnerID=40&md5=b051b4892b62d5cfd724317f1068cdfa","Institute for Lake Research - State Institute for Environment, Measurement and Nature Conservation of Baden-Württemberg, Argenweg 50/1, 88085 Langenargen, Germany; Fisheries Research Station of Baden-Württemberg, Argenweg 50/1, 88085 Langenargen, Germany","Stich, H.B., Institute for Lake Research - State Institute for Environment, Measurement and Nature Conservation of Baden-Württemberg, Argenweg 50/1, 88085 Langenargen, Germany; Brinker, A., Fisheries Research Station of Baden-Württemberg, Argenweg 50/1, 88085 Langenargen, Germany","Between 1951 and 1979, total phosphorous concentrations in Lake Constance increased from 7 to 87 μgL -1. Following wastewater treatment, phosphorus levels were brought under control, returning to 7.6 μgL -1 by spring 2007. The biological and chemical data from 1980 to 2004 were first modelled by seasonal time series analyses and then used to create a general model. Excluding collinear variables allowed the data set to be condensed to six variables that could be fitted into a general linear model that explained ~ 75% of the observed annual variation in chlorophyll a. A clear seasonal influence was apparent, with chlorophyll a tracking trends in temperature and the progress of spring. A nonseasonal influence was also observed in the interaction of two biological components, the proportion of phytoplankton biomass available to Daphnia (i.e. the percentage of ingestible size &lt;30 μm) and the grazing intensity. In combination, these biotic variables had a negative impact on chlorophyll a levels. In contrast, the concentration of soluble reactive phosphorus (SRP) correlated positively with chlorophyll a. The effect of SRP showed a significant seasonal component, as it was more abundant in spring than at other times of year. In general, the model predicts a negative exponential response of chlorophyll a to further depletion of SRP in Lake Constance, while the temperature trends predicted by current global warming scenarios will result in a moderate increase in productivity. Data from 2005 to 2007 were used to verify the model. The modelled chlorophyll a values were nonbiased and showed a close match to the measured values (r 2: 75%). Thus the applicability, reliability, and informative value of the model for pelagic Lake Constance was confirmed. The approach might easily be applied to other waters. © 2009 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.","Chlorophyll; Climate change; Daphnia; Grazing; Lake management; Oligotrophication; Phosphor; Time series modelling","annual variation; biomass; chlorophyll a; climate change; computer simulation; concentration (composition); global warming; grazing pressure; lake ecosystem; numerical model; oligotrophic environment; phosphorus; phytoplankton; seasonal variation; stratified flow; temperature effect; time series analysis; trend analysis; Bodensee; Daphnia",,,,,,"Anders, P.J., Ashley, K.I., The clear-water paradox of aquatic ecosystem restoration (2007) Fisheries, 32, pp. 125-128; Anderson, N.J., Jeppesen, E., Sondergaard, M., Ecological effect6s of reduced nutrient loading (oligotrophication) on lakes: an introduction (2005) Freshwater Biology, 50, pp. 1589-1593; Anneville, O., Gammeter, S., Straile, D., Phosphorus decrease and climate variability: Mediators of synchrony in phytoplankton changes among European peri-alpine lakes (2005) Freshwater Biology, 50, pp. 1731-1746; Anneville, O., Ginot, V., Druart, J.C., Angeli, N., Long term study (1974-1998) of seasonal changes in the phytoplankton in Lake Geneva: A multi-table approach (2002) Journal of Plankton Research, 24, pp. 993-1007; Anneville, O., Molinero, J.C., Souissi, S., Balvay, G., Gerdeaux, D., Lo